}\par {\pard \posx1505 \posy310 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5757 \absw7340 \dxfrtext200 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s2 \posx1505 \posy310 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5757 \absw7340 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li64 \ri61 \sl-252 \tx64 \tqr \tx7278 this software will typically let you turn your C128 into a sophisticated music synthesizer, rivaling professional machines costing thousands of dollars. Many musicians, composers, and rock groups are already using the Commodore 64 as a synthesizer, and the C128 has all the music power of the C64.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s3 \posx1505 \posy310 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5757 \absw7340 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li65 \fi445 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx65 \tx510 \tqr \tx7289 On the other hand, you may be interested in learning how to write your own sound\_generation programs. If so, you'll find the Commodore 128, used in C128 mode, the ideal vehicle. The new BASIC 7.0 makes controlling the sound much easier than on previous Commodore com\-puters, and the instant feedback provided by BASIC means that you can easily experiment with the various statements until you achieve just the effect you like.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s4 \posx1505 \posy310 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5757 \absw7340 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi445 \ri53 \sl-260 \tx50 \tx495 \tqr \tx7286 Of course, you can also write programs in C64 mode\'97using BASIC 2.0\'97that generate sound. However, you will be at a considerable disad\-vantage, since the Commodore 64 (and the C64 mode on the Commodore 128) lack the BASIC commands which make programming sound in the C128 mode so easy. Instead, you must resort to using BASIC's POKE instruction to insert numbers into certain memory locations (which are in turn connected to the SID chip). Having to know what numbers to POKE in, and what memory locations to POKE them into, makes pro\-gramming sound effects considerably more difficult and inflexible in C64 mode than in C128 mode.\par 
}\sect \sectd \linex0 \linemod0 \sbknone \lndscpsxn \marglsxn1455 \margrsxn1525 \pard \sl-260 \tx50 \tx495 \tqr \tx7286 {\pard \posx1521 \posy6395 \phpg \pvpg \absh-348 \absw3008 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs30 \f1 \i \pard \s5 \posx1521 \posy6395 \phpg \pvpg \absh-348 \absw3008 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-312 \tx50 \tqr \tx2957 In the Chips with SID\par 
}\pard \sl-312 \tx50 \tqr \tx2957 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1515 \posy6797 \phpg \pvpg \absh-4487 \absw7348 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \plain \lang1033 \pard \s6 \posx1515 \posy6797 \phpg \pvpg \absh-4487 \absw7348 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx7297 The Commodore 128 has a special custom\_made chip, called SID (for Sound Interface Device), which handles all its sound generation tasks. This chip can produce three separate channels, (called voices) of sound at the same time. Thus the C128 can easily play music with three\_part harmony. The individual character of each of these three voices can be separately modified, so that one voice can sound like a trumpet, another like a guitar, and a third like a piano. This is achieved by modifying the waveform and the envelope of the sound. We'll describe what this means later in the chapter. By changing the envelope and waveform any of the three voices can also be made to produce a rich variety of sound effects, from machine guns and bombs falling, to the rustle of leaves on an autumn afternoon.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s7 \posx1515 \posy6797 \phpg \pvpg \absh-4487 \absw7348 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li53 \fi441 \ri68 \sl-259 \tx53 \tx494 \tqr \tx7279 Once you know how to use BASIC to create sounds, you can add sound effects or music to any program you write. Most people think about games when they think about sound effects, and certainly the Commodore is a perfect environment for creating games with great graphics and as\-tonishing sound effects. However, sound is also useful in programs besides\par 
}\pard \sl-259 \tx53 \tx494 \tqr \tx7279 {\pard \posx10756 \posy12 \phpg \pvpg \absh-315 \absw554 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s8 \posx10756 \posy12 \phpg \pvpg \absh-315 \absw554 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-175 \tx50 \tqr \tx503 \_sit\par 
}\pard \sl-175 \tx50 \tqr \tx503 {\pard \posx11232 \posy336 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1600 \absw7334 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s9 \posx11232 \posy336 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1600 \absw7334 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-257 \tx50 \tqr \tx7283 games, such as word\_processor and spreadsheet programs. For instance, keystrokes can be signalled by a small clicking sound, so you're sure you've pressed the key, and incorrect input can be signalled by beeps. The sound\_generating abilities of the Commodore 128 can even be used in electronics. For example, the C128 could generate a variety of wave\-forms, including white noise, to test audio and TV equipment.\par 
}\pard \sl-257 \tx50 \tqr \tx7283 {\pard \posx11256 \posy2254 \phpg \pvpg \absh-651 \absw4036 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs30 \f1 \i \pard \s10 \posx11256 \posy2254 \phpg \pvpg \absh-651 \absw4036 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-303 \tx50 \tqr \tx3985 What Equipment Do You Need to Use Sound?\par 
}\pard \sl-303 \tx50 \tqr \tx3985 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx11235 \posy2931 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5026 \absw7339 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \plain \lang1033 \pard \s11 \posx11235 \posy2931 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5026 \absw7339 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri65 \sl-267 \tx50 \tqr \tx7273 Although the Commodore 128 has the SID sound generator chip built into it, the output of this chip needs to be amplified by an external device before it is audible, since there is no amplifier or speaker built into the C128.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s12 \posx11235 \posy2931 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5026 \absw7339 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li56 \fi441 \ri61 \sl-263 \tx56 \tx497 \tqr \tx7277 Often, the TV set or monitor you're using as a display has an amplifier and speaker built in. The new Commodore 1902 color monitor, for ex\-ample, has these features, as well as a volume control. By connecting the audio output from the C128 (either from the TV outlet or the Direct Video connection) to your display device, you'll be able to hear the sounds the C128 is making. (See the diagram in the chapter on peripherals for where these connections are.)\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s13 \posx11235 \posy2931 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5026 \absw7339 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li63 \fi441 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx63 \tx504 \tqr \tx7288 You can also run this audio output to your stereo amplifier (although the sound will not be in stereo). This is useful if you're using a monitor without audio capability. With the volume turned up and the right pro\-gram, this can generate awe\_inspiring effects: you (and your neighbors too, if you're not careful) will swear that an intergalactic battle cruiser is passing overhead. Even at low volume levels your stereo amplifier will produce better sound, and will do a better job of reproducing the very high and very low tones of which the Commodore 128 is capable.\par 
}\pard \sl-261 \tx63 \tx504 \tqr \tx7288 {\pard \posx10677 \posy8213 \phpg \pvpg \absh-745 \absw5432 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs33 \f2 \b \pard \s14 \posx10677 \posy8213 \phpg \pvpg \absh-745 \absw5432 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-323 \tx50 \tqr \tx5381 Commercial Software and Hardware for Sound Generation\par 
}\pard \sl-323 \tx50 \tqr \tx5381 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx11253 \posy9009 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2142 \absw7333 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \plain \lang1033 \pard \s15 \posx11253 \posy9009 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2142 \absw7333 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri55 \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx7277 There is a wide variety of music software and add\_on hardware devices, such as keyboards, already available for the Commodore 64. All of these products will work with the Commodore 128 in C64 mode, and some may also work in C128 mode. Manufacturers are also beginning to produce products specifically for the C128 mode.\par 
