}\pard \sl-253 \tx50 \tqr \tx1870 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1538 \posy5150 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2403 \absw7348 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \plain \lang1033 \pard \s5 \posx1538 \posy5150 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2403 \absw7348 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li67 \ri50 \sl-259 \tx67 \tqr \tx7297 There are several programs on the market which teach you music, or teach you specifically about the music\_generation capabilities of the SID chip. These can provide a far more interactive and exciting environment for learning about music than traditional classroom methods.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs24 \f0 \pard \s6 \posx1538 \posy5150 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2403 \absw7348 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi440 \ri76 \sl-259 \tx50 \tx490 \tqr \tx7271 We've given you some idea of the capabilities of commercial sound\-generation software. But suppose you want to write your own sound\-generating programs? The next sections explore how sound works on the Commodore 128, and how you can use BASIC 7.0 to take control of the sound generation.\par 
