\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s5 \posx1806 \posy986 \phpg \pvpg \absh-5513 \absw7365 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li63 \fi485 \ri68 \sl-260 \tx63 \tx548 \tqr \tx7296 There are several aspects to specifying duration in music. First, there is tempo. The tempo specifies how long a measure is. A measure is a fundamental unit of music notation. There are a certain fixed number of notes in each measure. A note can be a whole note, a half note, which is half as long as a whole note, a quarter note (half as long as a half note), an eighth not\'e8, or a sixteenth note. The exact number of notes in a measure depends on the time of the music. For instance, if a musical piece is in 4/4 time, then there will be four quarter notes (or two half notes or one whole note) in a measure. If a piece is in 3/4 (waltz) time, then there will be three quarter notes in a measure.\par 
