\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s7 \posx1428 \posy3886 \phpg \pvpg \absh-4063 \absw7361 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li55 \fi443 \ri65 \sl-261 \tx55 \tx498 \tqr \tx7295 The electronic circuits that act as filters aren't perfect, so the cutoff frequencies are not exact. The frequencies on the "wrong" side of the cutoff will be transmitted to some extent, but the further a frequency is from the cutoff, the more it will be attenuated. Figure 7\_5 shows the effect of filters on the sound levels at a range of frequencies.\par 
}\pard \sl-261 \tx55 \tx498 \tqr \tx7295 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1445 \posy8132 \phpg \pvpg \absh-312 \absw1947 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s8 \posx1445 \posy8132 \phpg \pvpg \absh-312 \absw1947 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-268 \tx50 \tqr \tx1896 Bandpass Filter\par 
}\pard \sl-268 \tx50 \tqr \tx1896 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1430 \posy8494 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2914 \absw7333 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s9 \posx1430 \posy8494 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2914 \absw7333 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx7282 SID offers a third kind of filter called the bandpass filter. As its name implies, this circuit filters out both high and low frequencies, so that only those in the midrange can get through. In the case of this filter the term "cutoff" frequency is a misnomer, since the number used for this fre\-quency now specifies the point at which the sound will \fs25 \f2 \i pass \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 through the filter, rather than being cut off.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s10 \posx1430 \posy8494 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2914 \absw7333 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li51 \fi443 \ri54 \sl-258 \tx51 \tx494 \tqr \tx7278 Figure 7\_5 shows the effects of these three kinds of filters on the amplitude of sound transmitted at different frequencies.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s11 \posx1430 \posy8494 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2914 \absw7333 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li51 \fi443 \ri50 \sl-258 \tx51 \tx494 \tqr \tx7282 By combining the high\_and low\_pass filters you can create a filter which is the opposite of the band\_pass filter: it filters out mid\_range frequencies, rather than letting them pass through.\par 
}\pard \sl-258 \tx51 \tx494 \tqr \tx7282 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx11357 \posy505 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1852 \absw7326 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s12 \posx11357 \posy505 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1852 \absw7326 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi444 \ri53 \sl-256 \tx50 \tx494 \tqr \tx7272 Another aspect of the filters that can be varied is the resonance. This determines how the frequencies of the sound near the cutoff frequency behave, and can be modified to achieve varying degrees of "sharpness" in the resulting sound.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s13 \posx11357 \posy505 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1852 \absw7326 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li69 \fi444 \ri50 \sl-256 \tx69 \tx513 \tqr \tx7275 Something to note about the filters is that they operate on all three voices at once. Thus you can't use filters to emphasize the bass on one voice and the treble on another.\par 
}\pard \sl-256 \tx69 \tx513 \tqr \tx7275 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx11372 \posy2664 \phpg \pvpg \absh-372 \absw5114 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs30 \f3 \i \pard \s14 \posx11372 \posy2664 \phpg \pvpg \absh-372 \absw5114 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-319 \tx50 \tqr \tx5063 Ring Modulation and Synchronization\par 
}\pard \sl-319 \tx50 \tqr \tx5063 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx11383 \posy3084 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2656 \absw7340 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \plain \fs25 \lang1033 \pard \s15 \posx11383 \posy3084 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2656 \absw7340 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx7289 It is possible to combine two voices together to produce interesting mus\-ical effects. In ring modulation, the outputs of two voices are added together. This can produce the "ringing" effect heard in bells and gongs. In synchronization two voices are logically ANDed together. This can be used to produce a rising and falling sound, such as a mosquito might make, and other complex harmonic structures.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s16 \posx11383 \posy3084 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2656 \absw7340 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li55 \fi439 \ri68 \sl-262 \tx55 \tx494 \tqr \tx7271 This review has only scratched the surface of sound generation on the Commodore 128. There are many other ways to shape and modify sound, but at this point let's turn to the specifics of sound generation with BASIC.\par 
}\pard \sl-262 \tx55 \tx494 \tqr \tx7271 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx14035 \posy6804 \phpg \pvpg \absh-312 \absw2173 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \b \pard \s17 \posx14035 \posy6804 \phpg \pvpg \absh-312 \absw2173 \dxfrtext200 \qc \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx2122 Figure 7\_5. Filters\par 
