}\par {\pard \posx880 \posy572 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1538 \absw7886 \dxfrtext200 \fs33 \f0 \pard \s2 \posx880 \posy572 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1538 \absw7886 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri4609 \sl-363 \tx50 \tqr \tx3276 Sound and BASIC 7.0\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \plain \fs25 \f1 \lang1033 \pard \s3 \posx880 \posy572 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1538 \absw7886 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li620 \ri50 \sl-257 \tx620 \tqr \tx7835 In this section we'll describe the commands that BASIC 7.0 uses to control the sound and music capabilities of the SID chip. There are six of these statements: VOL, SOUND, ENVELOPE, PLAY, TEMPO, and FILTER. We'll describe each of these statements in turn.\par 
}\sect \sectd \linex0 \linemod0 \sbknone \lndscpsxn \marglsxn783 \margrsxn1464 \pard \sl-257 \tx620 \tqr \tx7835 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1479 \posy2437 \phpg \pvpg \absh-348 \absw2746 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs30 \f2 \i \pard \s4 \posx1479 \posy2437 \phpg \pvpg \absh-348 \absw2746 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-312 \tx50 \tqr \tx2695 The VOL Statement\par 
}\pard \sl-312 \tx50 \tqr \tx2695 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1450 \posy2843 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1087 \absw7308 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \plain \fs25 \f1 \lang1033 \pard \s5 \posx1450 \posy2843 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1087 \absw7308 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-258 \tx50 \tqr \tx7257 As we mentioned above, the volume of all three voices can be controlled together by one BASIC statement. This statement is VOL, for volume. This is one of the simpler statements, since it has only one parameter. Here's a typical program line in BASIC, using this statement:\par 
}\pard \sl-258 \tx50 \tqr \tx7257 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx876 \posy4156 \phpg \pvpg \absh-286 \absw1470 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs22 \f3 \pard \s6 \posx876 \posy4156 \phpg \pvpg \absh-286 \absw1470 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-232 \tx50 \tqr \tx1419 100 VOL 8\par 
}\pard \sl-232 \tx50 \tqr \tx1419 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1426 \posy4652 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2398 \absw7343 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s7 \posx1426 \posy4652 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2398 \absw7343 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li60 \fi441 \ri74 \sl-261 \tx60 \tx501 \tqr \tx7268 The possible settings for the volume range from 0 to 15, where 0 is off (no sound) and 15 is maximum.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s8 \posx1426 \posy4652 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2398 \absw7343 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \fi441 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tx491 \tqr \tx7292 Since you can adjust overall sound volume using the knob on your TV set or stereo, you may find yourself keeping the VOL at its highest level most of the time, and controlling individual notes with the sustain level. However VOL is useful in sound effects, and for turning the sound on and off. Notice however, that you must use \fs21 \f0 \i VOL \fs25 \f1 \plain \fs25 \f1 \lang1033 before you con use the SOUND statement to actually generate sound. You can't get any sound out of the SID chip until you've used VOL to select a non\_zero volume level.\par 
}\pard \sl-260 \tx50 \tx491 \tqr \tx7292 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1453 \posy7377 \phpg \pvpg \absh-348 \absw3212 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs30 \f2 \i \pard \s9 \posx1453 \posy7377 \phpg \pvpg \absh-348 \absw3212 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-312 \tx50 \tqr \tx3161 The SOUND Statement\par 
}\pard \sl-312 \tx50 \tqr \tx3161 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1410 \posy7782 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1613 \absw7329 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \plain \fs25 \f1 \lang1033 \pard \s10 \posx1410 \posy7782 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1613 \absw7329 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx7278 The SOUND statement is the keystone of BASIC \fs22 \f3 7.0's \fs25 \f1 sound effects capa\-bility. With it you can set the frequency, duration, sweep, and waveform of a sound. It's not usually used for playing music; the PLAY statement does that. SOUND is used for sound effects and other situations where you want very close control of the frequency and other characteristics of the sounds you're producing.\par 
}\pard \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx7278 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1422 \posy9589 \phpg \pvpg \absh-329 \absw3539 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f0 \pard \s11 \posx1422 \posy9589 \phpg \pvpg \absh-329 \absw3539 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-276 \tx50 \tqr \tx3488 The Simple Version of SOUND\par 
}\pard \sl-276 \tx50 \tqr \tx3488 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx1404 \posy9978 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1092 \absw7335 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s12 \posx1404 \posy9978 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1092 \absw7335 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri50 \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx7284 In its simplest form, SOUND can be used to set only the frequency and duration of a sound. You must also specify which voice is to be used, since every sound produced must be made by one of SID's three voices. For instance, the program line\par 
}\pard \sl-260 \tx50 \tqr \tx7284 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx833 \posy11275 \phpg \pvpg \absh-286 \absw2891 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs22 \f3 \pard \s13 \posx833 \posy11275 \phpg \pvpg \absh-286 \absw2891 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-232 \tx50 \tqr \tx2840 100 SOUND 2, 4291, 60\par 
}\pard \sl-232 \tx50 \tqr \tx2840 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx11298 \posy647 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2370 \absw7327 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s14 \posx11298 \posy647 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2370 \absw7327 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri63 \sl-255 \tx50 \tqr \tx7263 will cause a tone with the frequency of middle C to be played by voice number \fs22 \f3 2 \fs25 \f1 for one second. Lets look at the three parameters used in this statement.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s15 \posx11298 \posy647 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2370 \absw7327 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li68 \fi437 \ri55 \sl-256 \tx68 \tx505 \tqr \tx7271 The first parameter in SOUND (the \fs22 \f3 2 \fs25 \f1 in this case) specifies the voice. The range of choices here is from 1 to \fs22 \f3 3.\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s16 \posx11298 \posy647 \phpg \pvpg \absh-2370 \absw7327 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li63 \fi437 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx63 \tx500 \tqr \tx7276 The second parameter is the frequency. This is a number from 0 to \fs22 \f3 65535. \fs25 \f1 Unfortunately, this number does not correspond to the actual frequency of the sound. However, it's related to it by the following simple formula:\par 
}\pard \sl-261 \tx63 \tx500 \tqr \tx7276 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx12941 \posy3022 \phpg \pvpg \absh-312 \absw4166 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s17 \posx12941 \posy3022 \phpg \pvpg \absh-312 \absw4166 \dxfrtext200 \li50 \ri50 \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx4115 Parameter value = Frequency / \fs22 \f3 0.06097\par 
}\pard \sl-261 \tx50 \tqr \tx4115 \fs24 \f0 {\pard \posx11330 \posy3563 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1877 \absw7317 \dxfrtext200 \fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s18 \posx11330 \posy3563 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1877 \absw7317 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li50 \ri55 \sl-250 \tx50 \tqr \tx7261 Thus while the range of values for the frequency parameter runs from 0 to \fs22 \f3 65535, \fs25 \f1 the range of actual frequencies runs from 0 to about \fs22 \f3 4000 cps \fs25 \f1 (although values below about \fs22 \f3 40 cps will \fs25 \f1 sound more like a series of clicks than a tone).\par 
\fs10 \f0 \fs25 \f1 \pard \s19 \posx11330 \posy3563 \phpg \pvpg \absh-1877 \absw7317 \dxfrtext200 \qj \li56 \fi436 \ri50 \sl-263 \tx56 \tx492 \tqr \tx7266 Middle C on the musical scale has a frequency of \fs22 \f3 262 cps, so, \fs25 \f1 dividing this number by \fs22 \f3 0.06097, \fs25 \f1 we find the value of the parameter to generate this note is \fs22 \f3 4297. \fs25 \f1 Table \fs22 \f3 7\_1 \fs25 \f1 shows the frequencies and parameter values\par 
